    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that sock analogy makes sense. but what's the deal with the \"spooky\" part everyone talks about? like why did einstein call it spooky action at a distance? it sounds like there's some kind of hidden mechanism or something going on that we just can't see.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spooky action at a distance,\" as Einstein famously dubbed it, stems from the fact that this instantaneous correlation seems to violate the cosmic speed limit—the speed of light. If the particles are entangled, measuring one instantly influences the state of the other, even if they are light-years apart. Einstein was deeply uncomfortable with this because it implied some form of faster-than-light communication or influence, which he felt shouldn't exist. It's a real head-scratcher, even for the most seasoned physicist, and it's a concept that keeps the theoretical physics community buzzing about how to properly categorize it.",
      "source": "target",
